    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is a security best practice that dictates users should only have the minimum level of access necessary to perform their specific job functions. In a company network, this means a standard employee shouldn't have admin rights to the entire server, and a junior developer shouldn't be able to delete production databases.\n\nIt works by creating a strict hierarchy of permissions, much like how a goblin in a dark cave only needs a torch to light his immediate path, not the whole cavern. If a goblin tries to grab a giant sword from the treasure chest, he gets caught; similarly, if a user tries to access files they don't need, the system denies them access, preventing potential data breaches or accidental destruction.\n\nFor your certification study, think of it as a \"goblin's backpack\" analogy: a goblin only packs the exact tools he needs for the quest he's on. If he tries to carry a hammer when he only needs a pickaxe, he's clumsy and gets in the way. In IT, we configure roles so that a \"goblin\" (user) has just the right permissions to do the job, nothing more. This limits the damage if a goblin (user)",
      "source": "target",
