      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand you need the technical details for your exam, and I apologize for the earlier goblin tangents! I can certainly focus strictly on the network security implementation of the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) without the goblin metaphors.\n\nHere are the core technical implementation details for PoLP in a corporate network:\n\n1.  **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)**: This is the primary mechanism. Instead of granting permissions to individual users, permissions are assigned to specific roles (e.g., \"Finance Analyst,\" \"System Administrator,\" \"Guest\"). Users are then mapped to these roles. If a user's job duties change, you only update their role assignment, ensuring they never retain unnecessary privileges from a previous position.\n\n2.  **Principle of Separation of Duties (SoD)**: This prevents any single user from having conflicting or excessive power. For example, the user who creates a payment voucher should not be the same user who approves it or reconciles the bank statement. In network terms, this means separating read-only access from write-access and separating development environments from production environments.\n\n3.  **Just-In-Time (JIT) Access**: Instead of granting long-term administrative privileges, access is",
